  ✅ 1. Fix the 8 critical bugs — These cause wrong query results and data corruption
  ✅ 2. Add $guarded enforcement + $hidden — Security essentials
  ✅ 3. Add increment/decrement/sum/avg/min/max/value/pluck/exists — Highest-use missing features
  ✅ 4. Add selectRaw/whereRaw/havingRaw — Completes the raw SQL story
  5. Add create() — Common Eloquent pattern (toJson()/$hidden done — see ✅22/✅23; findOrFail()/firstOrFail() done — see ✅24)
  6. Enrich Collection — Bring it closer to Eloquent's rich collection API

Other works need to be done:
  - Extracted the correct OR-aware WHERE logic into a single reusable method
  - Iterates $this->wheres, preserving OR prefixes and defaulting to AND
  - Quotes dot-notation identifiers (table.column) automatically
  - buildDeleteQuery() — same bug fix — identical broken pattern replaced
  - update() — replaced 14 lines of duplicated OR-handling logic
  - $guarded enforcement confirmed: fill()/__set()/offsetSet() (and therefore
    updateOrCreate/firstOrCreate/firstOrNew/new Model([...])) all route through
    isFillableAttribute()/isGuardedAttribute(), so mass assignment already
    respects $guarded. newFromBuilder() intentionally bypasses it since it
    hydrates trusted data straight from the database.
  - Added $hidden (and $visible) support to Model: new $hidden/$visible
    properties, toArray()/toJson() now filter through applyVisibility(),
    plus getHidden()/setHidden()/getVisible()/setVisible()/makeHidden()/
    makeVisible() helpers (Eloquent-style). Collection::toJson() added too.
  - Added sum()/avg() (+ average() alias)/min()/max() to QueryBuilder, all
    backed by a shared protected aggregate() helper that swaps in a single
    aggregate SELECT, respects the current WHERE/JOIN/GROUP BY and the
    model's soft-delete scope, then restores the original select list so
    the builder instance stays reusable afterward.
  - Added value($column) — SELECTs just that column, reuses first(), and
    resolves dot-notation/aliased column names back to the correct result
    key via a new resultColumnName() helper.
  - Added pluck($column, $key = null) at the QueryBuilder level — queries
    only the requested column(s) directly (no full model hydration) and
    returns a flat array, or an associative array keyed by $key. Distinct
    from (and complements) the existing Collection::pluck(), which plucks
    from an already-fetched collection of hydrated models.
  - Added exists()/doesntExist() — short-circuits with LIMIT 1 and a
    minimal SELECT 1, cheaper than count() > 0 or checking first().
  - Added increment()/decrement() in two places:
      - QueryBuilder::increment()/decrement() — bulk, affects every row
        matching the current query via a single atomic
        UPDATE ... SET col = col +/- %s [, extra...] WHERE ... statement.
      - Model::increment()/decrement() (instance methods) — automatically
        scoped to the model's own primary key (so $user->increment('votes')
        only touches that one row, unlike the generic __call() proxy which
        would have run on an unscoped fresh query), and syncs the new
        value(s) onto the in-memory model afterward so no refresh() is
        needed. Both forms auto-touch updated_at when timestamps are
        enabled, unless the caller supplies it via the optional $extra
        array.
  - Updated Methods.md (new "Aggregates & Utility Methods" section + TOC
    entry) and Readme.md (Features list + new "Aggregates & Utility
    Methods" section with examples) to document all of the above.
  - Added selectRaw($sql, $bindings = []) — appends a raw expression to
    the SELECT list (combinable with select() and/or other selectRaw()
    calls); raw entries are stored as ['raw' => ..., 'bindings' => ...]
    so they bypass quoteIdentifier() entirely and carry their own bindings.
  - Added whereRaw()/orWhereRaw($sql, $bindings = []) — push a raw SQL
    fragment straight into $this->wheres (OR-prefixed for the orWhere
    variant), reusing the exact same OR-prefix detection that
    buildWhereClause() already applies to every other where*() method.
  - Added groupByRaw($sql, $bindings = []) — same raw-entry pattern as
    selectRaw(), for grouping by SQL expressions (e.g. DATE(created_at))
    rather than plain column names.
  - Added havingRaw()/orHavingRaw($sql, $bindings = []) — push directly
    into $this->havings using the same [$expr, $values] shape that
    having()/havingBetween() already use, so no changes were needed to
    the HAVING-rendering code in buildSelectQuery().
  - Fixed a binding-order bug surfaced while wiring this up: getBindings()
    previously returned WHERE bindings before HAVING/ORDER-BY-raw
    bindings but had no concept of SELECT- or GROUP-BY-raw bindings at
    all. Replaced the old single getSelectExtraBindings() helper with
    four focused helpers (getSelectBindings/getGroupByBindings/
    getHavingBindings/getOrderByBindings) and rebuilt getBindings() to
    merge them in true left-to-right SQL clause order: SELECT, WHERE,
    GROUP BY, HAVING, ORDER BY. This matters for any query mixing
    selectRaw()/groupByRaw() with regular where()/having() calls — count(),
    delete(), and update() are unaffected since they never touch the
    SELECT list and build their SQL independently of buildSelectQuery().
  - Updated buildSelectQuery()'s SELECT and GROUP BY rendering to detect
    and pass through raw entries (arrays with a 'raw' key) instead of
    running them through Helpers::quoteIdentifier().
  - Updated Methods.md (new "Raw SQL Expressions" section + TOC entry;
    also backfilled previously-undocumented orHaving()/orHavingBetween())
    and Readme.md (Features list + new "Raw SQL Expressions" section
    with examples, placed after "Custom Queries") to document all of the
    above.
  - Fixed CURRENT_TIMESTAMP (and similar raw SQL) default handling in
    ColumnDefinition::toSql() — string defaults were always wrapped in
    single quotes, so ->default('CURRENT_TIMESTAMP') produced
    DEFAULT 'CURRENT_TIMESTAMP' (a literal string) instead of
    DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP (the SQL keyword). toSql() now detects a
    small set of raw SQL default keywords/expressions — CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,
    CURRENT_TIMESTAMP(n), CURRENT_TIMESTAMP ON UPDATE CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,
    NOW(), NULL, TRUE, FALSE, UUID() — case-insensitively, via a new
    isRawDefaultExpression() helper, and emits them unquoted. Plain
    string defaults are still quoted as before, but now also have
    embedded single quotes escaped (e.g. ->default("o'brien")), which
    was a latent SQL-breaking bug in the old unconditional
    "'{$this->default}'" interpolation. Numeric and boolean defaults are
    unaffected (already rendered unquoted; booleans now explicitly map to
    1/0 rather than relying on PHP's truthy string coercion). This does
    not change the existing ...WithDefault() Blueprint column-type
    shortcuts (e.g. timestampWithDefault()), which already embedded
    CURRENT_TIMESTAMP directly into the column type string rather than
    going through ->default().
  - Added chunk($count, $callback) on QueryBuilder — processes results in
    pages instead of loading the whole result set into memory at once.
    Internally drives the existing limit()/offset()/get() machinery on the
    same builder instance (the same pattern paginate()/simplePaginate()
    already use), so it automatically respects whatever where()/join()/
    soft-delete scoping is already on the query. The callback receives a
    Collection of up to $count models plus the current page number; returning
    false from the callback stops iteration early (chunk() then returns
    false), otherwise chunk() returns true once it runs out of rows.
  - Added each($callback, $count = 1000) on QueryBuilder — same underlying
    paging as chunk(), but invokes the callback once per individual model
    (with a running zero-based $index) instead of once per page. Returning
    false from the callback stops iteration early. Implemented as a thin
    wrapper around chunk() rather than duplicating the paging loop.
  - Updated Methods.md (new entries under Retrieval Methods / a new
    "Batch Processing" section + TOC entry) and Readme.md (Features list +
    new "Processing Large Datasets: chunk() and each()" section with
    examples) to document both methods.
  - Hardened Model::toJson() and Collection::toJson() for production use:
    both previously called json_encode() directly and would silently return
    `false` on failure (e.g. malformed UTF-8 in an attribute, or a NAN/INF
    float produced by a cast), which could leak a corrupt/empty payload
    downstream with no diagnostic. Both now check json_last_error() and
    throw a \JsonException with a descriptive message (model class name
    included for Model::toJson()) on failure — matching Eloquent's
    JsonEncodingException behavior — instead of swallowing the error.
  - Added Model::__toString() and Collection::__toString() (Eloquent-style)
    — both return the same output as toJson(), so models/collections can be
    used directly in string contexts (echo $user;, string interpolation,
    logging) without an explicit ->toJson() call. Safe on PHP 7.4+ (this
    package's minimum supported version), where __toString() is allowed to
    throw exceptions normally.
  - Updated Methods.md (toJson() entry now documents the \JsonException
    behavior + try/catch example; new __toString() entry for both Model and
    Collection) and Readme.md (new "Serialization: toJson()" section
    covering toJson()/__toString()/exception handling, placed after "Array
    Conversion and Casting"; Collection's "Available Methods" table updated
    with __toString() and toJson()'s exception note) to document all of the
    above.
  - Added findOrFail()/firstOrFail() (Eloquent-style), in three places:
      - New MJ\WPORM\ModelNotFoundException class (extends \RuntimeException)
        — carries the offending model's class name (getModel()) and, for
        findOrFail(), the id(s) that were searched for (getIds()), with an
        Eloquent-style "No query results for model [...]" message built via
        setModel($model, $ids = null).
      - QueryBuilder::findOrFail($id) / QueryBuilder::firstOrFail() —
        thin wrappers around the existing find()/first() (which themselves
        already wrap get()), so they run the exact same single query and
        still trigger retrieved() on a hit; only a null-check + throw is
        added, no extra DB round-trip. Works mid-chain, e.g. after with()
        or withTrashed().
      - Model::findOrFail($id) (static) — mirrors Model::find()'s existing
        shape/behavior (including its own explicit retrieved() trigger),
        just adds the not-found throw.
      - Model::firstOrFail(array $attributes = []) (static) — builds
        static::query()->where($attributes)->first() (an empty array is a
        no-op where(), matching Eloquent's "first record overall" fallback
        behavior) and throws if nothing matched.
  - Updated composer.json's PSR-4 root mapping already covers the new
    ModelNotFoundException.php (flat file at the package root, same as
    Model.php/Collection.php/etc.) — no composer.json change needed.
  - Updated Readme.md (Features list; new "Finding a Record or Failing:
    findOrFail and firstOrFail" section placed after "Querying by a
    Specific Column"; added ModelNotFoundException.php to the Manual
    Installation require list) and Methods.md (new findOrFail()/
    firstOrFail() entries under Retrieval Methods, directly after find())
    to document all of the above.
